What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113937 observations with the 80 variables that concern the data regarding a loan grouped as:

  • loan data
  • borrower data
  • borrowing company revenue per loan data
  • loan investors

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in how the socio-economic factors pertaining to the borrower are distributed among the users of Prosper

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

My expectation is that people who are employed, are homeowners, have a high income and low debt are more represented

for a better view of the data we shall split the graph in two, the one for the ratios between 0 and 2 and the other for the other data values

In [47]:
# defining the figure size 
plt.figure(figsize = [10, 5])
# separating the data in : 1st set 
data_set1 = loans.query('DebtToIncomeRatio < 1')['DebtToIncomeRatio']
# ... and second set
data_set2 = loans.query('DebtToIncomeRatio > 1')['DebtToIncomeRatio']
# defining the position in the subplot
plt.subplot(2, 1, 1)
# defining the bin edges 
bin_edges = np.arange(0, data_set1.max(), 0.02)
# plotting the first graph
plt.hist(data_set1, bins = bin_edges, color=base_color);
# defining the position for the second graph 
plt.subplot(2, 1, 2)
# defining the bin edges 
bin_edges = np.arange(1, data_set2.max(), 0.2)
# plotting the graph 
plt.hist(data_set2, bins = bin_edges, color=base_color);

Now we can see more clearly how the distributions are drawn. Also the values a bit higher than 1 display an unusual pattern

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The last analysed variable, the debt to income ratio, the range of the values is so high that I had to split the grapsh into two in order to be able to visualize the data accordingly.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Most of the data would not fit into normal countplot graph, this is why chose to display most of the data horizontaly.

# feature engineering: building the past_due_tf on wether the LoanStatus is Past or Default
loans['past_due_tf'] = loans['LoanStatus'].str.contains('Past|Default')
In [49]:
# defining the size of the figure
plt.figure(figsize=(10,12))
# choosin the base color palette

No observable corelation between the income and "defaultness" can be observed
